P rate, g rate and pg rate for the 148 countries included in this example were computed respectively using the following three equations:8.1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ p\  rate=\frac{N}{P}\left(\mathrm{per}\ 1000\ \mathrm{population}\right) $$
\end{document}Prate=NPper1000population
8.2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ g\  rate=\frac{N}{A}\left(\mathrm{per}\ 100\ {\mathrm{km}}^2\right) $$
\end{document}Grate=NAper100km2
8.3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ pg\  rate=\frac{N}{P\times A}\left(\mathrm{per}\ \mathrm{million}\ \mathrm{population}\cdot 100\ {\mathrm{km}}^2\right) $$
\end{document}PGrate=NP×Apermillion population⋅100km2
